The paper introduces a variable importance measure to explain the importance of individual variables to a decision made by a black box function. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) or artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper uses cooperative game theory to develop the Shapley value, which is a common technique in machine learning and AI. The paper also discusses the problematic approach of changing the value of one or more variables with the others held fixed, which suggests that the paper may also belong to the data structures (cs.DS) or computer engineering (cs.CE) sub-categories. Finally, the paper discusses the potential for creating unrealistic combinations of predictors, which suggests that the paper may also belong to the cryptography and security (cs.CR) sub-category.
